    12	
    13	# deep-improvement
    14	
    15	Improve an agent the way you ship code: change a copy, measure it, and promote only when the evidence holds.
    16	
    17	---
    18	
    19	## 1. OVERVIEW
    20	
    21	### What This Skill Does
    22	
    23	Editing an agent prompt is usually guesswork. You reword a rule, the prompt reads better, you ship it, and you never know whether the agent got stronger or only different. `deep-improvement` replaces that guess with measured evidence.
    24	
    25	The skill treats agent improvement as an optimization problem with a paper trail. It scans every surface an agent touches across the repo, derives a scoring profile from the agent's own rules, writes a candidate to a packet-local sandbox, scores it across five deterministic dimensions, and promotes to the canonical file only after evidence and an operator approval both pass. Nothing touches the real agent until you say so.
    26	
    27	For packet recovery around an improvement run, `/speckit:resume` stays the canonical surface. Continuity rebuilds from `handover.md`, then `_memory.continuity`, then the remaining spec docs.
    28	
    29	### Three Lanes
    30	
    31	This skill runs three co-equal lanes that share one evaluator core, journal, and promotion discipline:
    32	
    33	| Lane | Use it to | Command |
    34	|---|---|---|
    35	| **Lane A — Agent-Improvement** | Improve a bounded agent `.md` file (the default; most of this README) | `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` |
    36	| **Lane B — Model-Benchmark** | Benchmark a model or prompt framework against fixtures | `/deep:start-model-benchmark-loop` |
    37	| **Lane C — Skill-Benchmark** | Diagnose a skill's real-world routing, discovery, efficiency, and usefulness | `/deep:start-skill-benchmark-loop` |
    38	
    39	Lane B (the model-benchmark mode) is documented in `SKILL.md` §4 and `references/model-benchmark/`; Lane C (the skill-benchmark mode) in `references/skill-benchmark/`. To match the three lanes, `references/`, `assets/`, and `scripts/` are each split into `agent-improvement/`, `model-benchmark/`, `skill-benchmark/`, and `shared/` subdirs.
    40	
    41	### What Changes With This Skill
    42	
    43	| Without it | With it |
    44	|---|---|
    45	| Prompt edits are ad hoc and untracked | Every candidate is packet-local and evidence-backed |
    46	| Quality is judged by reading the prompt file | Quality is scored across five deterministic dimensions |
    47	| Integration drift goes unnoticed | The scanner checks mirrors, commands, skills, and routing |
    48	| Promotion risk is hard to audit | Promotion, rollback, and drift review each leave explicit artifacts |
    49	| Only hand-profiled agents can be evaluated | Any agent in `.opencode/agents/` is evaluated through dynamic profiling |
    50	
    51	### How This Compares
    52	
    53	The `@deep-improvement` agent (under `.opencode/agents/`) is the mutator that writes one candidate. This skill is the evaluator and the rulebook around it: it owns scoring, benchmarking, the promotion gates, and the stop logic. `sk-prompt` rewrites prompt prose on request. This skill decides whether a rewrite earned its place.
    54	
    55	### Key Features at a Glance
    56	
    57	| Capability | What It Does |
    58	|---|---|
    59	| Integration scanning | Maps every file that references an agent across the repo |
    60	| Dynamic profiling | Derives scoring rules from the agent's own ALWAYS/NEVER/ESCALATE IF sections |
    61	| 5-dimension scoring | Measures structural integrity, rule coherence, integration consistency, output quality, and system fitness |
    62	| Proposal-first edits | Candidates live in a packet-local sandbox, never the canonical file |
    63	| Guarded promotion | Canonical mutation only after scoring, benchmark, repeatability, boundary, and approval all pass |
    64	| Rollback | Restores the pre-promotion backup and records a post-rollback dimensional snapshot |
    65	| Runtime-truth contracts | Stop-reason taxonomy, legal-stop gates, and an append-only journal, matching deep-research and deep-review |
    66	
    67	### Requirements
    68	
    69	- An existing spec folder for the improvement run
    70	- Node.js 18+ for the `.cjs` scripts
    71	- A target agent file in `.opencode/agents/`
    72	- Packet-local runtime write access
    73	
    74	---
    75	
    76	## 2. QUICK START
    77	
    78	**Step 1: Pick a target and a spec folder.**
    79	
    80	Choose any agent under `.opencode/agents/` and the phase spec folder where the run will live.
    81	
    82	**Step 2: Run the loop.**
    83	
    84	```text
    85	/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop ".opencode/agents/debug.md" :confirm --spec-folder={spec_folder}
    86	```
    87	
    88	Expected result: an integration scan, a packet-local candidate under `candidates/`, a five-dimension score, a benchmark report, and a refreshed dashboard.
    89	
    90	**Step 3: Run a single script when you only need one signal.**

