    36	
    37	## 2. EVALUATION LOOP
    38	
    39	**Lane:** Lane A (agent-improvement)
    40	
    41	These entries cover the session lifecycle from fresh runtime setup through proposal-only candidate generation, scoring dispatch, guarded promotion, rollback, and the stop logic that decides when the loop should stop asking for more iterations.
    42	
    43	### Initialization
    44	
    45	#### Description
    46	
    47	Sets up a fresh packet-local deep-improvement session before any candidate work begins.
    48	
    49	#### Current Reality
    50	
    51	The shipped workflow only supports fresh `new` sessions. Both YAML workflows create `{spec_folder}/improvement/`, scan the target integration surface, generate a dynamic profile when requested, copy the config, strategy, charter, and manifest templates, record baseline state, and emit a `session_start` journal row before iteration one.
    52	
    53	#### Source Files
    54	
    55	See [`01--evaluation-loop/01-initialization.md`](01--evaluation-loop/01-initialization.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.
    56	
    57	---
    58	
    59	### Candidate generation
    60	
    61	#### Description
    62	
    63	Writes one bounded packet-local candidate without mutating the canonical target.
    64	
    65	#### Current Reality
    66	
    67	Candidate generation is delegated to the `deep-improvement` subagent. That agent must read the copied charter and manifest first, must write only under the packet-local runtime area, returns structured metadata, and stops before scoring, benchmarking, promotion, or mirror synchronization begins.
    68	
    69	#### Source Files
    70	
    71	See [`01--evaluation-loop/02-candidate-generation.md`](01--evaluation-loop/02-candidate-generation.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.
    72	
    73	---
    74	
    75	### Scoring dispatch
    76	
    77	#### Description
    78	
    79	Routes a generated candidate through scoring, evidence recording, and state reduction.
    80	
    81	#### Current Reality
    82	
    83	The loop dispatches `score-candidate.cjs`, records mutation coverage, writes journal events, and refreshes the dashboard with `reduce-state.cjs`. Benchmark stability and trade-off checks are wired as concrete commands, while the benchmark runner itself still appears as an action placeholder in the YAML workflows, so fully automatic benchmark execution depends on operator wiring or wrapper logic outside the YAML text.
    84	
    85	#### Source Files
    86	
    87	See [`01--evaluation-loop/03-scoring-dispatch.md`](01--evaluation-loop/03-scoring-dispatch.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.
    88	
    89	---
    90	
    91	### Promotion gates
    92	
    93	#### Description
    94	
    95	Defines the narrow conditions under which a packet-local candidate can become promotion-eligible.
    96	
    97	#### Current Reality
    98	
    99	The policy surface requires explicit approval, benchmark pass, repeatability pass, manifest compliance, and a meaningful improvement threshold. The promotion helper is stricter than the current scorer output: it still requires `candidate-better` plus `score.delta`, while `score-candidate.cjs` currently emits `candidate-acceptable` or `needs-improvement` and does not add a delta field.
   100	
   101	#### Source Files
   102	
   103	See [`01--evaluation-loop/04-promotion-gates.md`](01--evaluation-loop/04-promotion-gates.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.
   104	
   105	---
   106	
   107	### Rollback
   108	
   109	#### Description
   110	
   111	Restores the archived canonical target after a guarded promotion has already happened.
   112	
   113	#### Current Reality
   114	
   115	Rollback is a separate helper, not an implicit part of promotion. The shipped rollback script validates the runtime config target and the single canonical target in the manifest, then copies the saved backup over the canonical file; journal emission, mirror review, and post-rollback re-scoring remain separate orchestration steps.
   116	
   117	#### Source Files
   118	
   119	See [`01--evaluation-loop/05-rollback.md`](01--evaluation-loop/05-rollback.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.
   120	
   121	---
   122	
   123	### Plateau detection
   124	
   125	#### Description
   126	
   127	Stops the loop when repeated runs no longer produce useful movement.
   128	
   129	#### Current Reality
   130	
   131	Two stop models are live. `reduce-state.cjs` can stop when all tracked dimensions plateau with exact repeated scores across the configured plateau window, while `mutation-coverage.cjs`, `trade-off-detector.cjs`, and `benchmark-stability.cjs` separately gate convergence, trade-off analysis, and replay stability behind a minimum of three scored samples.
   132	
   133	#### Source Files
   134	
   135	See [`01--evaluation-loop/06-plateau-detection.md`](01--evaluation-loop/06-plateau-detection.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.
   136	
   137	---
   138	
   139	## 3. INTEGRATION SCANNING
   140	
   141	**Lane:** Lane A (agent-improvement)
   142	
   143	These entries describe how deep-improvement discovers the full agent surface across the repo, evaluates runtime mirrors, and wires command-driven orchestration through the deep-improvement command and YAML workflows.
   144	
   145	### Surface discovery
   146	
   147	#### Description
   148	
   149	Builds the inventory of files and references that define an agent beyond its canonical markdown file.
   150	
   151	#### Current Reality
   152	
   153	`scan-integration.cjs` scans the canonical agent file, three runtime mirrors, improve command markdown, YAML workflow assets, skill references, global docs, and a skill-advisor path constant. That path now points at `.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/scripts/skill_advisor.py`, so the consolidated skill-advisor surface is included in the integration map.
   154	
   155	#### Source Files
   156	
   157	See [`02--integration-scanning/01-surface-discovery.md`](02--integration-scanning/01-surface-discovery.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.
   158	
   159	---
   160	
   161	### Runtime mirrors
   162	
   163	#### Description
   164	
   165	Checks whether the runtime-specific mirrors still reflect the canonical agent body closely enough.
   166	
   167	#### Current Reality
   168	
   169	Mirror parity is signal-based, not byte-for-byte. The scanner strips frontmatter, extracts up to three emphasized signal strings from the canonical body, and marks a mirror `aligned` when at least two signals appear in the mirror body. It checks `.claude/agents`, `.codex/agents`, and `.gemini/agents` against the canonical `.opencode/agents`.
   170	
   171	#### Source Files
   172	
   173	See [`02--integration-scanning/02-runtime-mirrors.md`](02--integration-scanning/02-runtime-mirrors.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.
   174	
   175	---
   176	
   177	### Command dispatch
   178	
   179	#### Description
   180	
   181	Owns the command-driven orchestration path that turns the deep-improvement skill into a runnable loop.
   182	
   183	#### Current Reality
   184	
   185	The `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` command collects setup inputs, selects `:auto` or `:confirm` execution, and points the operator at the matching YAML workflow. The actual loop dispatch lives in the YAML assets, which rescan integration, dispatch `@deep-improvement`, emit journal events, and call score and reducer helpers, while the command markdown explicitly says not to dispatch agents from the command file itself.
   186	
   187	#### Source Files
   188	
   189	See [`02--integration-scanning/03-command-dispatch.md`](02--integration-scanning/03-command-dispatch.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.
   190	
   191	---
   192	
   193	## 4. SCORING SYSTEM
   194	
   195	**Lane:** Shared (Lane A scores candidates, Lane B can opt into the same 5-dim scorer)
   196	
   197	These entries describe the dynamic scoring stack that derives evaluation structure from the target agent, applies the five-dimension rubric, records deterministic score outputs, and turns repeated runs into dimensional progress and stop-state summaries.
   198	
   199	### Five-dimension rubric
   200	
   201	#### Description
   202	
   203	Defines the weighted evaluation model used to judge prompt-surface quality.
   204	
   205	#### Current Reality
   206	
   207	Dynamic scoring uses five weighted dimensions: structural integrity, rule coherence, integration consistency, output quality, and system fitness. Each dimension has a concrete checker in `score-candidate.cjs`, with integration itself delegated to the integration scanner and output quality penalized when placeholder strings remain in the candidate.
   208	
   209	#### Source Files
   210	
   211	See [`03--scoring-system/01-five-dimension-rubric.md`](03--scoring-system/01-five-dimension-rubric.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.
   212	
   213	---
   214	
   215	### Dynamic profiling
   216	
   217	#### Description
   218	
   219	Generates a target-specific evaluation profile directly from the agent being scored.
   220	
   221	#### Current Reality
   222	
   223	No static evaluation profiles ship in the current release. `generate-profile.cjs` parses frontmatter, sections, rules, output checklists, related-resource tables, and denied permissions to build a derived profile on the fly, while `target_manifest.jsonc` keeps `targets` empty and points runtime consumers at the dynamic-profile script instead of a fixed catalog.
   224	
   225	#### Source Files
   226	
   227	See [`03--scoring-system/02-dynamic-profiling.md`](03--scoring-system/02-dynamic-profiling.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.
   228	
   229	---
   230	
   231	### Deterministic scoring
   232	
   233	#### Description
   234	
   235	Produces the score and benchmark evidence that later gates consume.
   236	
   237	#### Current Reality
   238	
   239	`score-candidate.cjs` always runs in `dynamic-5d` mode, regenerates the profile every run, allows optional weight overrides, and emits structured dimension details plus `candidate-acceptable` or `needs-improvement`. `run-benchmark.cjs` is also deterministic, but it still expects a profile JSON and fixture directory under `assets/agent-improvement/target-profiles`, so benchmark gating only becomes runnable when that profile-specific artifact set exists.
   240	
   241	#### Source Files
   242	
   243	See [`03--scoring-system/03-deterministic-scoring.md`](03--scoring-system/03-deterministic-scoring.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.
   244	
   245	---
   246	
   247	### Dimensional progress
   248	
   249	#### Description
   250	
   251	Reduces raw run records into trends, best-known state, and operator-facing stop guidance.
   252	
   253	#### Current Reality
   254	
   255	`reduce-state.cjs` aggregates the JSONL ledger into `experiment-registry.json` and `agent-improvement-dashboard.md`, records latest and best values per dimension, adds sample-quality, journal, lineage, and mutation-coverage summaries, and computes stop status. It treats both `candidate-acceptable` and `candidate-better` as accepted candidates when building the registry.
   256	
   257	#### Source Files
   258	
   259	See [`03--scoring-system/04-dimensional-progress.md`](03--scoring-system/04-dimensional-progress.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.
   260	
   261	---
   262	
   263	## 5. MODEL-BENCHMARK MODE
   264	
   265	**Lane:** Lane B (model-benchmark)
   266	
   267	These entries describe the model-benchmark path that benchmarks a model or prompt framework instead of mutating an agent file. They cover the mode switch in the loop host, the model-agnostic dispatcher, the opt-in five-dimension scorer, and the record-level mode field plus the two hardening env gates.
   268	
   269	### Mode switch
   270	
   271	#### Description
   272	
   273	Routes loop-host between the agent-improvement scorer and the model-benchmark materialize-then-run pipeline.
   274	
   275	#### Current Reality
   276	
   277	`scripts/shared/loop-host.cjs` resolves `--mode` before any work begins. `--mode=agent-improvement`, or no flag, routes to `scripts/agent-improvement/score-candidate.cjs` unchanged; `--mode=model-benchmark` runs `scripts/shared/materialize-benchmark-fixtures.cjs` then `scripts/model-benchmark/run-benchmark.cjs`; and `--mode=skill-benchmark` runs `scripts/skill-benchmark/run-skill-benchmark.cjs` (Lane C). `VALID_MODES` is a closed three-value set, and an unknown mode warns to stderr and falls back to `agent-improvement`.
   278	
   279	#### Source Files
   280	
   281	See [`04--model-benchmark-mode/01-mode-switch.md`](04--model-benchmark-mode/01-mode-switch.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.
   282	
   283	---
   284	
   285	### Model dispatcher
   286	
   287	#### Description
   288	
   289	Model-agnostic dispatcher that routes prompts across executor CLIs only on the model-benchmark path.
   290	
   291	#### Current Reality
   292	
   293	`scripts/model-benchmark/dispatch-model.cjs` routes through an executor map across cli-opencode, cli-claude-code, cli-codex, cli-gemini, and cli-devin, and is loaded only on the model-benchmark path, never in agent-improvement mode. It forwards `cwd` to every executor and applies rate-limit backoff using a non-busy `Atomics` sleep.
   294	
   295	#### Source Files
   296	
   297	See [`04--model-benchmark-mode/02-model-dispatcher.md`](04--model-benchmark-mode/02-model-dispatcher.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.
   298	
   299	---
   300	
   301	### Opt-in 5-dimension scorer
   302	
   303	#### Description
   304	
   305	Selects the pattern matcher by default or the opt-in five-dimension scorer for model-benchmark outputs.
   306	
   307	#### Current Reality
   308	
   309	`run-benchmark.cjs --scorer pattern` is the default byte-identical heading and pattern matcher, while `--scorer 5dim` routes materialized outputs through `scripts/model-benchmark/scorer/score-model-variant.cjs`, the ported five-dimension scorer. `--grader noop` is the default deterministic grader with no model dispatch, with `--grader mock` and `--grader llm` selecting the stub or real grader, and the report carries `scoringMethod: pattern` or `scoringMethod: 5dim`.
   310	
   311	#### Source Files
   312	
   313	See [`04--model-benchmark-mode/03-opt-in-5dim-scorer.md`](04--model-benchmark-mode/03-opt-in-5dim-scorer.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.
   314	
   315	---
   316	
   317	### Mode records and hardening gates
   318	
   319	#### Description
   320	
   321	Stamps a mode field on every state record and exposes two env gates that harden the 5-dim scorer.
   322	
   323	#### Current Reality
   324	
   325	Every state record carries `mode: agent-improvement` or `mode: model-benchmark`, and benchmark reports plus `benchmark_run` records carry `scoringMethod: pattern|5dim`. `DEEP_AGENT_ALLOW_CRITERIA_EXEC=0` refuses criteria-driven shell execution in the 5-dim scorer, and `DEEP_AGENT_GRADER_CACHE_RAW=0` redacts raw grader output from the on-disk cache. Both default to the permissive value for backward-compat.
   326	
   327	#### Source Files
   328	
   329	See [`04--model-benchmark-mode/04-mode-records-and-gates.md`](04--model-benchmark-mode/04-mode-records-and-gates.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.
   330	
   331	---
   332	
   333	## 6. SKILL-BENCHMARK MODE
   334	
   335	**Lane:** Lane C (skill-benchmark)
   336	
   337	These entries describe the skill-benchmark path that diagnoses how a *skill* is routed-to, discovered, used, and structured in practice — distinct from doc-shape validation and manual testing playbooks. It is diagnostic by default and emits a ranked Skill Benchmark Report. Mode A (router-replay) and D1-inter (advisor probe) are deterministic; D4 usefulness ablation and live trace capture are follow-on.
   338	
   339	### Mode wiring and orchestration
   340	
   341	#### Description
   342	
   343	Routes loop-host to the skill-benchmark orchestrator with a single additive arm; the orchestrator runs the D5 gate, then per-scenario contamination-lint, router-replay, and scoring.
   344	
   345	#### Current Reality
   346	
   347	`scripts/shared/loop-host.cjs` resolves `--mode=skill-benchmark` to `scripts/skill-benchmark/run-skill-benchmark.cjs` via an additive `VALID_MODES` entry, `LANE_SKILL_BENCHMARK` set, and `planInvocation` arm; the agent-improvement and model-benchmark plans stay byte-identical.
   348	
   349	#### Source Files
   350	
   351	`scripts/shared/loop-host.cjs`, `scripts/skill-benchmark/run-skill-benchmark.cjs`.
   352	
   353	### Hint-free fixtures and contamination gate
   354	
   355	#### Description
   356	
   357	Per-skill public/private scenario fixtures keep the expected skill/intents/resources scorer-only; a contamination linter rejects public prompts that leak the answer before dispatch.
   358	
   359	#### Current Reality
   360	

