.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/006-deep-review/gpt55/iterations/iteration-003.md:4115:.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/z_archive/024-compact-code-graph/research/iterations/iteration-021.md:12:4. Fixture structure is mostly local and composable rather than centralized. The common fixture styles are: small object factories such as `makeTriggerMatch()` and `makeRow()` for pure logic tests; DB builders such as `createTestDb()` plus `seedTestMemories()` for storage-heavy tests; and filesystem fixtures where a suite synthesizes a temporary spec folder or markdown memory file on demand. `memory-save-ux-regressions.vitest.ts` is the clearest file-backed fixture example: it builds a realistic markdown memory document with frontmatter, anchored sections, and recovery metadata, writes it into `tmp-test-fixtures`, then cleans matching DB rows after each test. The README’s mention of `fixtures/` is accurate, but the representative suites reviewed here rely more on inline factory functions and generated temp fixtures than on broad shared static fixture imports. (`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/tests/dual-scope-hooks.vitest.ts:36-48`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/tests/handler-memory-search.vitest.ts:135-214`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/tests/handler-helpers.vitest.ts:101-190`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/tests/memory-save-ux-regressions.vitest.ts:43-152`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/tests/memory-save-ux-regressions.vitest.ts:158-233`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/tests/README.md:91-94`)
