.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/logs/synth.out:50002:-.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/103-spec-kit-auto-mode-noninteractive-contract/002-auto-mode-contract-generalization-to-all-commands/evidence/codex-group3-dispatch-full-transcript.txt:1367:.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.5.0.0.md:3:description: "Rename the agent across all 4 runtime mirrors plus YAML asset filenames and ~30 active reference files. Completes naming-family alignment with the skill folder rename from packet 079. The skill, agent, and command family now share one identity: deep-agent-improvement skill ↔ @deep-agent-improvement agent ↔ /deep:start-agent-improvement-loop command."
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/logs/synth.out:50019:-.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/103-spec-kit-auto-mode-noninteractive-contract/002-auto-mode-contract-generalization-to-all-commands/evidence/codex-group3-dispatch-full-transcript.txt:1384:.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.1.0.0.md:97:> This release documented four lifecycle modes for re-entering an `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` session: `resume`, `restart`, `fork`, and `completed-continue`. None of the four were ever wired up. The command has no input for lineage mode, the reducer does not carry ancestry across sessions, and the journal helper has no multi-session boundary event. Every invocation is a fresh `new` session.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/logs/synth.out:50021:-.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/103-spec-kit-auto-mode-noninteractive-contract/002-auto-mode-contract-generalization-to-all-commands/evidence/codex-group3-dispatch-full-transcript.txt:1386:.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.4.0.0.md:25:The old path `.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/` no longer resolves. Use `.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/` for skill files, references, assets, scripts, feature catalog entries, and manual testing playbooks. The agent name `@deep-agent-improvement` and command `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` are unchanged.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/logs/synth.out:50025:-.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/103-spec-kit-auto-mode-noninteractive-contract/002-auto-mode-contract-generalization-to-all-commands/evidence/codex-group3-dispatch-full-transcript.txt:1390:.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/changelog/v1.2.1.0.md:13:- **Resume/continuation expected behavior retracted to match reality** -- The skill's runtime-truth section and the `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` command definition both listed `resume`, `restart`, `fork`, and `completed-continue` as supported lifecycle modes for evaluating an agent across multiple sessions. The shipped workflow has no inputs for any of them, the reducer does not produce ancestry output, and the journal helper has no boundary event for a multi-session run history. The only thing the runtime actually supports is `new` - every `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` invocation starts a fresh session with generation 1. The documentation now says so explicitly. Operators who want to continue an evaluation should archive the prior `improve/` folder under a timestamped path and re-invoke the command. A future release that ships real multi-session run history will arrive with first-class event emission, reducer ancestry output, and replay coverage; until then, treat every invocation as a standalone evaluation.
